ment, and education, Weber points out that the law has done little to combat disability harassment. He recommends that arguments based on unused provisions of the ADA should be developed and new legal remedies advanced to address the problem. Disability Harassment also draws on case law to explore special problems of harassment in the public schools, and closes with an appeal to judges and lawmakers for expanded legal protection against harassment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aDiscrimination against people with disabilitiesxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aHarassmentxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aPeople with disabilitiesxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited States. 0aStudents with disabilitiesxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited States. 7aLAW / Disability.2bisacsh  aBuilding.  aMark.  aWeber.  aartificial.  aattitudinal.  abarriers.  aboth.  acivil.  adamaging.  adisability.  adisabled.  aenvironment.  aexamination.  aframes.  agroup.  aharassment.  ainsights.  amembers.  aminority.  amust.  anegotiate.  aoften.  apeople.  aphysical.  apremise.  arights.  ascholars.  astudies.  athat.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814795071423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814795071/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK